			<span class="kicker"><a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/main-topics/investment-banking/">Investment Banking</a> | <a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/other-topics/wall-street-earnings/">Wall Street Earnings</a></span>		</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Deutsche Bank Returns to Profit as Legal Costs Ease</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Jack Ewing			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-04-29T07:22:17+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">April 29, 2014 3:22 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">April 29, 2014 3:22 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/30/business/dbpix-deutsche/dbpix-deutsche-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/30/business/dbpix-deutsche/dbpix-deutsche-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/30/business/dbpix-deutsche/dbpix-deutsche-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000002851731" width="592" height="347" alt="The headquarters of Deutsche Bank in Frankfurt."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="347"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">The headquarters of Deutsche Bank in Frankfurt.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Ralph Orlowski/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/04/29/deutsche-bank-returns-to-profit-as-legal-costs-ease/" data-title="Deutsche Bank Returns to Profit as Legal Costs Ease" data-description="Deutsche Bank, Germanyâs largest, said it swung to a profit in the first quarter as it avoided the huge litigation expenses that characterized the end of 2013.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">FRANKFURT â <a class="tickerized" title="More information about Deutsche Bank AG" href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=DB&amp;inline=nyt-org">Deutsche Bank</a>, Germanyâs largest bank, said on Tuesday that it returned to profit in the first quarter as it avoided the huge litigation expenses that characterized the end of 2013.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But the bank also warned that its legal problems were far from over, adding that compliance with tougher regulations is likely to be a burden for several years to come. That point was underlinedÂ on TuesdayÂ as European regulators outlined plans to test banksâ ability to withstand a crisis.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Deutsche Bank, the main European competitor to large American investment banks like <a class="tickerized" title="More information about JPMorgan Chase &amp; Company" href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=JPM&amp;inline=nyt-org">JPMorgan Chase</a> and <a class="tickerized" title="More information about Goldman Sachs Group Inc" href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=GS&amp;inline=nyt-org">Goldman Sachs</a>, said first-quarter net profit fell 34 percent, to 1.1 billion euros, or $1.5 billion, from the period a year earlier. It said the results were in line with expectations.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The profit was an improvement from the last quarter of 2013, when the bank reported a loss of â¬1.4 billion because of legal expenses related to charges of past wrongdoing. The bank said revenue fell 11 percent, to â¬8.4 billion, from the first quarter of 2013, largely because of reduced revenue from investment banking.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Like many other large banks, Deutsche Bank is entangled in costly legal proceedings related to its behavior before the financial crisis. Deutsche Bank and its peers also face intense pressure from government regulators who are trying to avoid a repeat of the economic havoc created by the crisis, much of which has been blamed on excessive risk-taking by banks.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Anshu Jain, the co-chief executive of Deutsche Bank, said the cost of complying with new regulations, including higher capital requirements intended to improve banks&#8217; ability to absorb losses, will continue to be a burden.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe regulatory bar is getting higher,â Mr. Jain said during a conference call with analystsÂ on TuesdayÂ morning. But he also said the price was worth paying. âIn general,â he said, &#8220;I think this is good for the system.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The bank will also face additional litigation expenses in coming quarters, Stefan Krause, the bankâs chief financial officer, said during the conference call. But he said he was not yet able to give specifics.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Deutsche Bank is among the institutions accused of manipulating benchmark interest rates that are used to set rates on trillions of dollars of mortgages and other credit. The bank and others also face investigations into possible manipulation of foreign currency markets and the market for credit insurance.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe investigations underway have the potential to result in the imposition of significant financial penalties and other consequences for the bank,â Deutsche Bank said in its first-quarter earnings report.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Deutsche Bank announced on Monday that it would raise â¬1.5 billion in new capital to meet increased demands by regulators that banks reduce their dependence on borrowed money. The new capital, part of a plan to raise a total of â¬5 billion by the end of 2015, will take the form of debt securities that would convert to equity in a crisis.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In an example of the pressure coming from regulators, the European Banking Authority and the <a class="tickerized" title="More articles about European Central Bank" href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/e/european_central_bank/index.html?inline=nyt-org">European Central Bank</a> gave details of the so-called stress tests they plan to conduct later this year to ensure that banks are prepared for any future crises. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Banks, for example, will need to show they could withstand a decline in economic output in the <a class="tickerized" title="More articles about the European Union." href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/e/european_union/index.html?inline=nyt-org">European Union</a> of 2.2 percent this year, and an increase in unemployment of 0.6 percentage points. Slower growth and higher joblessness typically leads to an increase in people who cannot repay their bank loans.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Europe continues to suffer the effects of the financial crisis that began in 2008. It has been blamed on excessive risk-taking by banks as well as governments that borrowed more money than they could afford.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The tests will cover 124 banks in the European Union. They will be required to show they could withstand shocks such as a sharp decline in European growth, turmoil in emerging markets, or a steep increase in borrowing costs for governments. The results will be published in October, and banks that fail will be required to increase capital or take other measures to become less vulnerable, the European Banking Authority said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The European Central Bank, which is conducting stress tests on banks in the euro zone, said it would give banks six to nine months to make up any shortfalls in capital, and advised them to begin making plans now to do so.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Deutsche Bank said that Tier 1 capital, a key measure of the bankâs ability to absorb losses, declined to 9.5 percent of total assets in the first quarter from 16.9 percent in the previous quarter. Adjusting for new rules that will change the way Tier 1 capital is being calculated by regulators, the decline was much smaller â to 9.5 percent from 9.7 percent, Deutsche Bank said. The bank is within regulatory limits, though its capital is lower than many competitors.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The bank attributed the decline to tougher regulatory requirements that required it to recalculate its capital ratios.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The decline in profit during the first quarter was partly the result of lower revenue in investment banking, which Deutsche Bank attributed to reduced trading activity by clients unsettled by turmoil in emerging markets.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At the same time, the bank reduced the amount of money it set aside to cover problem loans, reflecting a strong economy in Germany.</p>
<footer class="story-footer">
